Country vs Post

Yang Xu

11/28/2016

Dataset processing

In order to work on identify forum activity pattern for different countries, subset (contains all nonnul country values) is used for the following analysis.

For this specific dataset, all the variables related to forumviews are zero contains no information. So I removed all these variables to clean the data.

The subset I used to discover post related pattern contains following variables:

‘IPCountryName’ ,‘AnyLectureActivity’,‘PercentWeeksActiveInForum’,‘TotalForumComments’,‘TotalForumPosts’ ,‘Comments.1’,‘Comments.2’, ‘Comments.3’, ‘Comments.4’, ‘Comments.5’, ‘Comments.6’, ‘Comments.7’, ‘Comments.8’,‘Posts.1’,‘Posts.2’,‘Posts.3’,‘Posts.4’,‘Posts.5’,‘Posts.6’,‘Posts.7’,‘Posts.8’,‘TotalEvents’,‘NumActiveDays’

Details

Correlation Check

First let’s check on the correlations between variables. The following graph is a visualization on lower triangle of the correlation matrix. Deeper color shade indicates stronger correlation between two varibles. Color red indicates negative correlation while navy stands for positive correlation.

Distribution

There are 167 countries in this dataset. However, to avoid biased analysis result, we check on the student enrollment number in each country and picked up first 20 countries to perform further analysis.

Let’s take a look at varibles distributions by country.

The plots above show out the distribution for each variable while different colors mean different countries. They give us a general idea about the dataset. The count of most of forum related activities is zero no matter which country it is. Comparing with comments data from other weeks, week 8 seems to have a different distribution.

Post & Comments

Test

Method

Multi kruskal Test is used to test for if they were from the same distribution. If the P value is less than 0.05 we reject the null hypothesis and say that the pattern for specfic variables differ by country.

## $AnyLectureActivity
## 
##  Kruskal-Wallis rank sum test
## 
## data:  AnyLectureActivity by IPCountryName
## Kruskal-Wallis chi-squared = 11659, df = 167, p-value < 2.2e-16
## 
##

Result

From the test result, only var Posts.5 (posts number for week 5) have nonsignificant p-values.

In other words, the distributions of other forum related variables for different countries are not the same.
